VENS WIFI PROTOCOL FOR FUJITSU SCANSNAP IX500

          Reverse-engineered from packet captures of the macOS
     ScanSnap Home application communicating with a ScanSnap iX500
     over WiFi.

          This document describes the network protocol used by
     Fujitsu ScanSnap scanners with WiFi capability (iX500, possibly
     iX1500 and others). The protocol is referred to as "VENS" after
     the magic bytes in every packet.

          Known to work with: ScanSnap iX500 (model FI-IX500A,
     Silex WiFi module). May work with other ScanSnap models that
     use WiFi — reports welcome.


OVERVIEW

          The protocol uses four network ports:

       Port   Proto  Direction         Purpose
       -----  -----  ----------------  ---------------------------
       53220  UDP    scanner -> bcast  Discovery announcements
       52217  UDP    client -> scanner Client registration
       53219  TCP    bidirectional     Session handshake (3 connections)
       53218  TCP    bidirectional     Scan commands and image data

          All multi-byte integers are big-endian (network byte
     order). The scanner's WiFi module is manufactured by Silex
     Technology (OUI 00:80:92).


PACKET FORMAT

          All TCP packets on ports 53218 and 53219 share a common
     envelope:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       0       4     Total packet length (including this header)
       4       4     Magic "VENS" (0x56454e53)
       8       4     Command/status field
       12      4     Reserved (usually 0)

          For client-to-scanner packets on 53218, the envelope is
     followed by a 16-byte MAC block:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       16      6     Client MAC address
       22      10    Zero padding

       32+     var   Command payload (see SCAN SESSION)


DISCOVERY (UDP PORT 53220)

          The scanner periodically broadcasts to
     255.255.255.255:53220. Packet is 48 bytes:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       0       4     Length (0x00000030 = 48)
       4       4     Magic "VENS"
       8       4     0x00000021
       12      4     0x00000000
       16      4     0x00000001
       20      4     0x00000000
       24      4     Scanner IP address
       28      6     Scanner MAC address
       34      14    Zero padding

          Many consumer WiFi access points block or do not forward
     these broadcasts. An alternative discovery method is to scan
     the local subnet for hosts with TCP ports 53218 and 53219
     both open.


REGISTRATION (UDP PORT 52217)

          The client sends three 32-byte UDP packets to the scanner
     on port 52217. Each packet has a different magic and flags
     value:

       Packet  Magic                Flags
       ------  -------------------  ------
       1       "VENS" (0x56454e53)  0x0010
       2       "ssNR" (0x73734e52)  0x0100
       3       "V2ss" (0x56327373)  0x1000

          Packet format:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       0       4     Magic (see above)
       4       4     0x00000000 (packets 1-2) or 0x00000001 (packet 3)
       8       4     Client IP address
       12      6     Client MAC address
       18      2     0x0000
       20      2     0xd7e0 (protocol version?)
       22      2     Flags (see above)
       24      8     Zero padding

          The macOS client sends this sequence 4 times. The scanner
     responds to the first packet (VENS) with a 132-byte device info
     response. The other two magics typically time out — this appears
     to be normal.

          Registration must be performed before the TCP handshake,
     and again after the init session before scanning.


TCP HANDSHAKE (PORT 53219)

          Three separate short-lived TCP connections are made to
     port 53219. On each connection, the scanner sends a 16-byte
     hello first.

     Connection 1 — Client Registration

          Client sends a 128-byte registration packet:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       0       4     Length (0x00000080 = 128)
       4       4     "VENS"
       8       4     0x00000011
       12      4     0x00000000
       16      6     Client MAC address
       22      10    Zero padding
       32      4     0x00000006
       36      1     0x1e
       37      7     Zero padding
       44      4     0x00000001
       48      4     Client IP address
       50      2     0xd7e1 (callback port = 55265)
       52      12    Pairing key (see PAIRING KEY)
       64      16    Zero padding
       80      2     Year (big-endian, e.g. 0x07ea = 2026)
       82      1     Month
       83      1     Day
       84      1     Hour
       85      1     Minute
       86      1     Second
       87      1     0x00
       88      8     Unknown (observed: 0x36c7c7e47a800000)
       96      4     0xffff9d90
       100     28    Zero padding

          Scanner responds with 20 bytes. Byte offset 8 contains a
     signed big-endian 32-bit status code:

        0   Success
       -1   Bad packet format
       -2   Scanner serial mismatch
       -3   Unknown pairing key
       -4   Session busy / stale session
       -5   No serial in packet
       -7   Client IP mismatch (scanner paired to different client)

     Connection 2 — Device Query

          Client sends 32 bytes with command field 0x00000013.
     Scanner responds with 112 bytes containing the device name
     (e.g. "iX500-XXXXXXXXXX") as an ASCII string.

     Connection 3 — Session Confirm

          Client sends 32 bytes with command field 0x00000030.
     Scanner responds with 32 bytes.

          Connections 2 and 3 are made concurrently with the init
     session from background threads.


PAIRING KEY

          The 12-byte ASCII string at offset 52 of the registration
     packet is the pairing key. This is the serial number of the
     Silex WiFi module inside the scanner — not the ScanSnap product
     serial number.

          The scanner validates this key against its own WiFi module
     serial. If the key is wrong, the scanner responds with error
     -3. If the key is correct but the client IP does not match the
     paired client, the scanner responds with error -7.

          The pairing key is established when the scanner is first
     configured via the ScanSnap Home application (macOS/Windows).
     The scanner never sends this key to the client — the client
     must already know it.

          To obtain the key on Linux without the official software,
     broadcast discovery packets on the local network while ScanSnap
     Home is running on another machine. ScanSnap Home will
     automatically attempt to register and send its 128-byte
     handshake packet containing the key. The real scanner must be
     powered off or disconnected during this process to prevent
     ScanSnap Home from connecting to it instead.


SCAN SESSION (TCP PORT 53218)

          All scan communication happens over TCP port 53218. The
     scanner sends a 16-byte hello when the connection is
     established.

          Commands are sent as VENS packets (see PACKET FORMAT) with
     a 16-byte MAC block followed by a command payload. Each command
     gets a response in the same VENS packet format.

     Init Session

          A first TCP:53218 connection is used to initialize the
     scanner state. Commands are sent sequentially:

       Step  Cmd   Payload description
       ----  ----  -------------------
       1     0x12  Set mode (96 bytes payload)
       2     0xE7  Query firmware info
       3     0xC2  Query device status (32 bytes response)
       4     0xE6  Query parameter (variant a: read)
       5     0xE6  Query parameter (variant b: write)
       6     0xD5  Set parameter (0x08, 0x08)
       7     0xD6  Release session

          The connection is closed after the D6 release. This
     prepares the scanner for a new scan session.

     Scan Sequence

          A second TCP:53218 connection is used for the actual scan:

       Step  Cmd   Payload description
       ----  ----  -------------------
       1     0xC2  Query device status
       2     0xD5  Set parameter (0x08, 0x08)
       3     0xD8  Set parameter (zeros)
       4     0xE9  Set scan area (DPI, width, height)
       5     0xD4  Set scan config (color mode, DPI, dimensions)
       6     0xC2  Re-query device status
       7     0x03  Set ready (with 0x12 sub-type)
       8     0xE0  Prepare for scan
       9     0x0C  Start scan (with page counter)

     Scan Config (0xD4)

          The D4 command configures the scan. Key fields in its
     80-byte payload:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       17      1     Color mode (0x03 = color)
       18      1     0x01
       19      1     0x01
       20      2     0xd000
       22      2     0xc180
       24-29   6     0x808090 8080 00
       48      1     0x30
       50      1     0x01
       52      2     DPI (big-endian, e.g. 0x012c = 300)
       54      2     DPI (repeated)
       56      2     Unknown (0x0581)
       60      4     Width in pixels (big-endian)
       64      4     Height in pixels (big-endian)
       68      1     0x04

          For A4 at 300 DPI, the captured values are:
     Width: 0x000028d0 (10448), Height: 0x000044dc (17628).

          These do not match the expected 210/25.4*300 = 2480
     pixels. The scanner appears to use a different coordinate
     system, possibly related to its maximum optical resolution.

     Scan Start (0x0C)

          The scan start command includes a page counter and side
     indicator:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       0       4     0x0000000c
       4       1     0x00
       5       1     0x30 (even pages) or 0xb0 (odd pages = back side)
       ...
       10      1     Page counter (0, 1, 2, 3, ...)

          Even page numbers are front sides, odd are back sides
     (the scanner always scans duplex).

     Per-page Flow

          After the initial scan start, each page follows this
     pattern:

     Front side (even page counter):
       1. Receive JPEG image data
       2. Send 0x03 (ready) command
       3. Send next scan start (odd counter, back side)

     Back side (odd page counter):
       1. Receive JPEG image data
       2. Send 0x03 (ready)
       3. Send done query (0x0C variant with 0x80 flag)
       4. Receive response — check if more pages
       5. Send 0xC2 query
       6. Send 0xE0 prepare
       7. Send 0x03 ready
       8. Check response: if last 12 bytes are all zero, more
          pages follow
       9. Send next scan start (even counter, front side)

     Session Release (0xD6)

          After scanning is complete (or on error), the client MUST
     send a D6 release command on a new TCP:53218 connection.
     Failure to do so leaves the scanner in a busy state, causing
     error -4 on the next handshake.

       Command: 00000006 00000000 00000000 00000000
                d6000000 00000000 00000000 00000000

          The scanner responds with 40 bytes. After D6, close the
     connection.


IMAGE DATA FORMAT

          The scanner responds to the scan start command with image
     data:

       Offset  Size  Field
       ------  ----  -----
       0       16    VENS header (length covers entire response)
       16      16    MAC block
       32      10    Image sub-header
       42      var   JPEG data (starts with 0xFFD8)

          The JPEG stream contains a comment marker with the string
     "PFU ScanSnap #iX500". The stream ends with 0xFFD9.

          Multiple pages are sent as a continuous stream on the same
     TCP connection. The client must locate FFD8..FFD9 boundaries to
     split individual pages.


ERROR RECOVERY

          If the scanner is in a busy state (error -4 on handshake),
     send a D6 release on TCP:53218 before retrying. Sequence:

       1. Connect to TCP:53218
       2. Read 16-byte hello
       3. Send D6 release command (see SESSION RELEASE)
       4. Read response
       5. Close connection
       6. Wait 1 second
       7. Retry from registration

          If the feeder is empty, the scanner sends an error
     response instead of image data after the scan start command.


NOTES FOR OTHER SCANNER MODELS

          This protocol was documented from an iX500. If you are
     testing with a different ScanSnap model:

     - The port numbers (53218, 53219, 52217, 53220) are likely
       the same
     - The VENS magic and packet envelope should be identical
     - Command payloads (especially D4 scan config) may differ
     - The scan area values in E9/D4 may need adjustment
     - The 128-byte registration packet on 53219 may need
       different fields

          If you capture traffic from a different model, please
     share your findings so this document can be updated.


